      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Personal</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The Personal series is small and contains Todd Family correspondence and scrapbook materials. Of particular interest to the researcher should be the perceptive and observant Civil War letters written by Joseph L. Carlisle, of the Michigan 25th Infantry. Mr. Carlisle was a cousin of Fred P. Todd's wife, Mary Costello Todd.</p>
        </scopecontent>
        <c02 level="file">
          <did>
            <container type="box" label="Box">1</container>
            <unittitle>Civil War letters <unitdate type="inclusive" normal="1862/1865">1862-1865</unitdate></unittitle>
          </did>
          <odd>
            <p>(mostly written by Joseph L. Carlisle, Michigan 25th Infantry)</p>
          </odd>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="file">
          <did>
            <container type="box" label="Box">1</container>
            <unittitle>Miscellaneous letters written in <unitdate type="inclusive" normal="1908">1908</unitdate> to George Normahls, family relative, recuperating from tuberculosis in New Mexico</unittitle>
          </did>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="file">
          <did>
            <container type="box" label="Box">1</container>
            <unittitle><genreform normal="Scrapbooks">Scrapbook</genreform> (mostly clippings), <unitdate type="inclusive" normal="1895/1935">1895-1935</unitdate></unittitle>
          </did>
        </c02>
      </c01>
      <c01 level="series">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Savings and Loan Institutions</unittitle>
        </did>
        <scopecontent>
          <p>The Savings and Loan Institutions series is primarily devoted to the three institutions in which Fred P. Todd, Sr. and his son, J. Beecher Todd, worked and served as officers. Major sequences within the series are: General; National Loan and Investment Company; Surety Savings and Loan Association; and Surety Federal Savings and Loan Association. Each sequence is organized topically. Minutes from Board of Directors meetings; annual reports; organizational material; and scrapbooks are helpful in tracing the activities and history of each institution. News and Good Living, quarterly publications of Surety Savings and Surety Federal Savings, are brief in scope and general in content, but do contain semi-annual financial statements, promotional advertisements, and occasional employee-related information.</p>
        </scopecontent>
